04465nam a22006495i 9780292794689DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212007txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927946897 a10.7560/7171832doi  a(DE-B1597)588179  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a330.972/12221 aAnderson, Joan B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFifty Years of Change on the U.S.-Mexico Border :bGrowth, Development, and Quality of Life /cJoan B. Anderson, James Gerber. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (285 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction. The United States–Mexico Border -- tChapter 1. Along the United States–Mexico Border -- tChapter 2. Population Growth and Migration -- tChapter 3. U.S. Border States and Border Relations -- tChapter 4. Trade, Investment, and Manufacturing -- tChapter 5. The Environment -- tChapter 6. Formal and Informal Labor -- tChapter 7. Income, Equity, and Poverty -- tChapter 8. Living Standards -- tChapter 9. Human Development in the Border Region -- tChapter 10. The Future of United States–Mexico Border Regions -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe U.S. and Mexican border regions have experienced rapid demographic and economic growth over the last fifty years. In this analysis, Joan Anderson and James Gerber offer a new perspective on the changes and tensions pulling at the border from both sides through a discussion of cross-border economic issues and thorough analytical research that examines not only the dramatic demographic and economic growth of the region, but also shifts in living standards, the changing political climate, and environmental pressures, as well as how these affect the lives of people in the border region. Creating what they term a Border Human Development Index, the authors rank the quality of life for every U.S. county and Mexican municipio that touches the 2,000-mile border. Using data from six U.S. and Mexican censuses, the book adeptly illustrates disparities in various aspects of economic development between the two countries over the last six decades. Anderson and Gerber make the material accessible and compelling by drawing an evocative picture of how similar the communities on either side of the border are culturally, yet how divided they are economically. The authors bring a heightened level of insight to border issues not just for academics but also for general readers. The book will be of particular value to individuals interested in how the border between the two countries shapes the debates on quality of life, industrial growth, immigration, cross-border integration, and economic and social development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aIndustrial clusterszMexican-American Border Region. 0aLabor supplyzMexican-American Border Region. 0aMigrant laborzMexican-American Border Region. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aFoster, Lisa.1 aGerber, James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71718340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292794689423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292794689/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK